(1840, 338, 'info', '<strong>Title:</strong> The Coffin’s Too Big for the Hole by Kuo Pau Kun\r\n<strong>Presented by:</strong> LASALLE Diploma in Performance\r\n<strong>Director:</strong> Matt Grey\r\n<strong>Performer:</strong> Gauraangi Chopra, Khyan Kotak\r\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018\r\n<strong>Duration:</strong> 40 minutes no interval\r\n<strong>Location:</strong> Haque Centre of Acting &amp; Creativity (HCAC)\r\n<strong>Dates and Timings:</strong> 25 January 7pm, 26 January 6.30pm\r\n<strong>Medium:</strong> Theatre'),
(1841, 338, '_info', 'field_5a4c876ac506d'),
(1842, 338, 'description', 'The Coffin is Too Big for the Hole is one of Singapore’s best-known monologues. Written by the late Kuo Pao Kun, a single unnamed man takes us through his story about his efforts to bury his late grandfather in the standard-sized plot that is unfortunately too small for his late grandfather’s coffin. This is a fresh retelling of Kuo Pau Kun’s popular satirical monologue, conveyed by a young Indian woman (Gauraangi Chopra) using a variety of devices including live camera, shadow play and mask. They combine to create a production that is both contemporary and traditional, creating a space where the imagination can meet the playwright both in the present and across time and culture.\r\n\r\nThis production was highly praised when it was first presented at Le Festival Des Ecoles, in Limoges, France in June 2018.'),
(1843, 338, '_description', 'field_5a4c8765c506c'),
