(10, 1, '2017-12-06 13:57:52', '2017-12-06 05:57:52', 'LASALLE College of the Arts and Singapore Tourism Board (STB), with the support of the Little India Shopkeepers’ and Heritage Association (LISHA), present ARTWALK Little India, a multi-disciplinary public art project set in the cultural precinct of Little India. \r\n\r\nThe inaugural edition of ARTWALK was in 2015 and the event has been held as part of Singapore Art Week ever since. \r\n\r\nThrough artworks such as wall murals, films, music and performances, artists bring to life the history and traditions of Little India, as well as the personal stories of its community through a multi-sensory art experience.', 'About the Event', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about', '', '', '2019-01-17 12:00:33', '2019-01-17 04:00:33', '', 0, 'http://artwalklittleindia.sg/adm/?page_id=10', 1, 'page', '', 0),
(11, 1, '2017-12-06 13:57:59', '2017-12-06 05:57:59', 'In the 1840s, Little India served as a residential area for Europeans who were drawn to the elite sport of horse racing. With the development of cattle trading, traders began to hire Indian migrant workers, turning Little India into a thriving trade and community hub. Places of worship, such as Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple and Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple, as well as businesses and services were set up to cater to the needs of the Indian community. \r\n\r\nToday, Little India is one of Singapore’s most vibrant precincts, with events, festivals and celebrations held throughout the year.', 'Little India', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'little-india', '', '', '2019-01-17 12:01:09', '2019-01-17 04:01:09', '', 0, 'http://artwalklittleindia.sg/adm/?page_id=11', 2, 'page', '', 0),
